explanation: OS_NetworkGetID_Impl — The body/semantics of this callee determine whether the condition (OS_NetworkGetID_Impl(&IdBuf) != OS_SUCCESS) can ever be true. If the implementation always returns OS_SUCCESS the failure branch (return -1) is unreachable; if it can return other values the branch is reachable. OS_SUCCESS — The constant/value used in the comparison. To prove reachability you must know its definition/value (and whether it can alias other return codes). UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType — Present in the static call graph; if OS_NetworkGetID_Impl is generated as a UT stub or interacts with the UT framework, this symbol (and its behavior) can affect what return values the stub can produce (and thus branch reachability). UT_ExecuteBasicHandler — As above: part of the UT stub execution path that may be invoked by the implementation/stub; its behavior can determine the actual return value and so whether the failure path is feasible. UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr — Used by UT stubs to supply return values; required to understand whether the stub/UT framework can force a non-OS_SUCCESS result or always supplies OS_SUCCESS. int32 — The typedef of the return/local type to confirm the range and representation (signedness/size) of the returned hardcoded value (-1) and of values produced by the impl; although not directly affecting reachability logic, it is required for a complete MISRA reachability/semantics analysis.
